    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 0.0,
      "end": 5.88,
      "text": "This is a LibraVox recording. All LibraVox recordings are in the public domain.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 6.88,
      "end": 15.5,
      "text": "For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibraVoxLIBRIVOX.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 16.02,
      "end": 24.4,
      "text": "Recorded by Lee Dunkleberg for it with Texas. Dunkleberg. D-U-N-K-E-L-B-E-R-G.com.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 26.46,
      "end": 29.46,
      "text": "Asom's fables, the two soldiers and the robber.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 32.5,
      "end": 38.66,
      "text": "Two soldiers traveling together were set upon by a robber. One of them ran away,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 39.54,
      "end": 44.56,
      "text": "but the other stood his ground and laid about him so lustily with his sword",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 44.56,
      "end": 48.36,
      "text": "that the robber was fain to fly and leave him in peace.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 48.36,
      "end": 56.26,
      "text": "When the coast was clear, the timid one ran back, and flourishing his weapon",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 56.26,
      "end": 58.3,
      "text": "cried in a threatening voice.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 58.92,
      "end": 65.06,
      "text": "Where is he? Let me get at him, and I'll soon let him know whom he's got to deal with.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-010",
      "start": 66.06,
      "end": 67.18,
      "text": "But the other replied,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-011",
      "start": 69.0,
      "end": 74.2,
      "text": "You are a little late, my friend. I only wish you had backed me up just now,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-012",
      "start": 74.2,
      "end": 78.84,
      "text": "even if you had done no more than speak, for I should have been encouraged,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-013",
      "start": 78.84,
      "end": 80.82,
      "text": "believing your words to be true.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-014",
      "start": 82.14,
      "end": 87.08,
      "text": "As it is, calm yourself and put up your sword. There is no further use for it.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-015",
      "start": 88.24,
      "end": 91.62,
      "text": "You may delude others into thinking you're as brave as a lion,",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-016",
      "start": 92.34,
      "end": 100.96,
      "text": "but I know that at the first sign of danger, you run away like a hare.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-017",
      "start": 102.8,
      "end": 105.5,
      "text": "End of the Two Soldiers and the Robber.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
